# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: debug-adapter-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] In software development, a **breakpoint** is an intentional stopping or pausing place in a program, put in place for debugging purposes.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] It is also sometimes simply referred to as a **pause**.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] More generally, a breakpoint is a means of acquiring knowledge about a program during its execution.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] During the interruption, the programmer inspects the test environment (general-purpose registers, memory, logs, files, etc.) to determine whether the program is functioning as expected.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] In practice, a breakpoint consists of one or more conditions that determine when a program's execution should be interrupted.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Breakpoints were invented for ENIAC, one of the earliest digital computers, by programmer Betty Holberton.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] In the initial design of ENIAC, program flow was set by plugging cables from one unit to another.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] To make the program stop at a certain point, a cable was removed, called a *breakpoint*.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Early mainframe computers, such as the IBM/360, had console switches/dials that allowed breakpoints at specific instruction storage addresses and provided "single cycle" operation, permitting the contents of registers and memory to be observed directly on console lights.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] The advent of multitasking limited the use of this option since the entire machine was halted.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Programmers have used machine code patches to implement single destructive breakpoints to cause a core dump since the early days of computers.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] The core dump provided the state of the registers and memory at the exact moment of the deliberate "crash".
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] This also permitted step-by-step program execution in a true program animation manner with optional register and memory alterations simultaneously displayed.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Initially this type of animation was at the level of disassembled or decompiled machine code, but later advanced to HLL source level animation.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Breakpoints are most commonly used to interrupt a running program immediately before the execution of a programmer-specified instruction.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] This is often referred to as an *instruction breakpoint*.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Other kinds of conditions can also be used, such as the reading, writing, or modification of a specific location in an area of memory.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] This is often referred to as a *data breakpoint*, or a *watchpoint*.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Many systems also support breakpoints that are only active if a condition is met (such as a variable having a certain value), usually referred to as *conditional breakpoint*.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] When a breakpoint is hit, various tools are used to inspect the state of the program or alter it.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Stack trace of each thread may be used to see the chain of function calls that led to the paused instruction.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] A list of *watches* allows one to view the values of selected variables and expressions.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] There may also be tools to show the contents of registers, loaded program modules and other information.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] A *logpoint* is a type of breakpoint that only prints (or "logs") information instead of interrupting execution.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Usually the developer can specify a message and/or values of variables to print when execution reaches a specific point.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Logpoints are an alternative to putting logging statements into the program being debugged (sometimes called *printf debugging*), and particularly helpful when changing the program is not practical (for example when debugging an external library called by the program).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Many processors include hardware support for breakpoints (typically instruction and data breakpoints).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] As an example, the x86 instruction set architecture provides hardware support for breakpoints with its x86 debug registers.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Such hardware may include limitations, for example not allowing breakpoints on instructions located in branch delay slots.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] This kind of limitation is imposed by the microarchitecture of the processor and varies from processor to processor.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Without hardware support (and in multitasking environments), debuggers have to implement breakpoints in software.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] This technique may be more difficult to implement in multitasking systems using shared program storage (the interrupt may occur on a different thread, requiring resurrection of the original instruction for that thread).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Also, if the program resides in protected memory, overwriting of instructions may be prevented.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Some debuggers allow registers or program variables in memory to be modified before resuming, effectively allowing the introduction of "hand-coded" temporary assignments for test purposes.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Similarly, program instructions can often be skipped to determine the effect of changes to the program logic – enabling questions about program execution to be answered in a direct way (i.e. without assumptions or guesswork).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] In many cases it may be the only practical method of testing obscure "event-driven" error subroutines that rarely, if ever, get executed – without the added risk of leaving temporary source changes.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Manually changing the resume location within a paused program can be used to enter an otherwise rarely executed section of code (such as a specific hardware condition handler).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Implementing data breakpoints in software however, can greatly reduce the performance of the application being debugged – since it is using additional resources on the same processor.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] However, this is normally acceptable during testing and the amount of information available from the debugger is not restricted by limitations of debug data known to the hardware.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] For instance, a software implementation can collect logical path data at program/subroutine/instruction level to considerably augment what might be stored by the particular hardware platform for inspection.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] The instruction set simulation method considerably reduces the overhead, compared to the (repeated) instruction replacement method, also reducing cache misses.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Some programming language implementations expose their debugging functions for use by other programs.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] For example, some FORTRAN dialects have an `AT` statement, which was originally intended to act as an instruction breakpoint.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] Python implements a debugger accessible from a Python program.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/breakpoint] These facilities can be and are abused to act like the COMEFROM statement.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debug-adapter-protocol] The Debug Adapter Protocol (DAP) defines the abstract protocol used between a development tool (e.g.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debug-adapter-protocol] Adding a debugger for a new language to an IDE or editor is not only a significant effort, but it is also frustrating that this effort can not be easily amortized over multiple development tools, as each tool uses different APIs for implementing the same feature.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debug-adapter-protocol] The idea behind the *Debug Adapter Protocol* (DAP) is to abstract the way how the debugging support of development tools communicates with debuggers or runtimes into a protocol.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debug-adapter-protocol] Since it is unrealistic to assume that existing debuggers or runtimes adopt this protocol any time soon, we rather assume that an intermediary component - a so called *Debug Adapter* - adapts an existing debugger or runtime to the Debug Adapter Protocol.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debug-adapter-protocol] The Debug Adapter Protocol makes it possible to implement a generic debugger for a development tool that can communicate with different debuggers via Debug Adapters.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debug-adapter-protocol] And Debug Adapters can be re-used across multiple development tools which significantly reduces the effort to support a new debugger in different tools.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debug-adapter-protocol] The *Debug Adapter Protocol* is a win for both debugger providers and tooling vendors!
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debug-adapter-protocol] The protocol defines the format of the messages sent using JSON between the development tool and the debug adapter.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debug-adapter-protocol] The latest version of the protocol specification is version 1.71.0.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debug-adapter-protocol] The DAP has been implemented for many debuggers or runtimes and some development tools are hosting these debug adapters.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] A **debugger** is software for executing a computer program in an environment that allows for programming-level inspection and control.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] A debugger is often used to debug, but can be used for other goals including testing.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Common features of a debugger include stepping through code line-by-line, breaking into the program's flow of control, managing breakpoints, and reporting and modifying memory.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] **symbolic debugger**) provides a user experience that integrates the program's source code.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Typically, such a debugger can indicate which line of source code corresponds to the execution point of the program and allows for reading and writing memory via the symbols of the source code.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] In contrast, a **low-level debugger** (a.k.a.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] **machine-language debugger**) shows the execution point as machine code or its associated assembly language and allows memory access by address only.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Some debuggers offer two modes of operation, full or partial simulation, to limit this impact.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Typically, debuggers offer a query processor, a symbol resolver, an expression interpreter, and a debug support interface at its top level.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] It may also be possible to continue execution at a different location in the program to bypass a crash or logical error.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] The same functionality which makes a debugger useful for correcting bugs allows it to be used as a software cracking tool to evade copy protection, digital rights management, and other software protection features.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] It often also makes it useful as a general verification tool, fault coverage, and performance analyser, especially if instruction path lengths are shown.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Most mainstream debugging engines, such as gdb and dbx, provide console-based command line interfaces.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Debugger front-ends are popular extensions to debugger engines that provide IDE integration, program animation, and visualization features.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] If a program is running with a debugger, and an exception occurs because of a programming bug or invalid data, the debugger is notified of the exception.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] When the program "traps" or reaches a preset condition, the debugger typically shows the location in the original code if it is a source-level debugger or symbolic debugger.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] If it is a low-level debugger or a machine-language debugger it shows the line in the disassembly (unless it also has online access to the original source code and can display the appropriate section of code from the assembly or compilation).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Record and replay debugging, also known as "software flight recording" or "program execution recording", captures application state changes and stores them to disk as each instruction in a program executes.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] The recording can then be replayed and interactively debugged to diagnose and resolve defects.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Record and replay debugging is useful for remote debugging and for resolving intermittent, non-deterministic, and other hard-to-reproduce defects.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Some debuggers include a feature called "**reverse debugging**", also known as "historical debugging" or "backwards debugging".
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] These debuggers make it possible to step a program's execution backwards in time.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Microsoft Visual Studio (2010 Ultimate edition, 2012 Ultimate, 2013 Ultimate, and 2015 Enterprise edition) offers IntelliTrace reverse debugging for C#, Visual Basic .NET, and some other languages, but not C++.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Reverse debuggers also exist for C, C++, Java, Python, Perl, and other languages.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Some are open source; some are proprietary commercial software.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Some reverse debuggers slow down the target by orders of magnitude, but the best reverse debuggers cause a slowdown of 2× or less.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Reverse debugging is very useful for certain types of problems, but is not commonly used.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] In addition to the features of reverse debuggers, time travel debugging also allow users to interact with the program, changing the history if desired, and watch how the program responds.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Some debuggers operate on a single specific language while others can handle multiple languages transparently.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] For example, if the main target program is written in COBOL but calls assembly language subroutines and PL/1 subroutines, the debugger may have to dynamically switch modes to accommodate the changes in language as they occur.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Some debuggers also incorporate memory protection to avoid storage violations such as buffer overflow.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] This may be extremely important in transaction processing environments where memory is dynamically allocated from memory 'pools' on a task by task basis.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Some processors have hardware support for single-stepping a program, such as the trap flag.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Some of the most capable and popular debuggers implement only a simple command line interface (CLI)—often to maximize portability and minimize resource consumption.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Developers typically consider debugging via a graphical user interface (GUI) easier and more productive.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] This is the reason for visual front-ends, that allow users to monitor and control subservient CLI-only debuggers via graphical user interface.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Some GUI debugger front-ends are designed to be compatible with a variety of CLI-only debuggers, while others are targeted at one specific debugger.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Debugging is often used to illegally crack or pirate software, which is usually illegal even when done non-maliciously.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] Crackme's are programs specifically designed to be cracked or debugged.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugger] These programs allow those with debuggers to practice their debugging ability without getting into legal trouble.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] In engineering, **debugging** is the process of finding the root cause, workarounds, and possible fixes for bugs.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] For software, debugging tactics can involve interactive debugging, control flow analysis, log file analysis, monitoring at the application or system level, memory dumps, and profiling.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Many programming languages and software development tools also offer programs to aid in debugging, known as debuggers.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] The term *bug*, in the sense of defect, dates back at least to 1878 when Thomas Edison wrote "little faults and difficulties" in his inventions as "Bugs".
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] A popular story from the 1940's is from Admiral Grace Hopper.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] While she was working on a Mark II computer at Harvard University, her associates discovered a moth stuck in a relay that impeded operation and wrote in a log book "First actual case of a bug being found".
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Although probably a joke, conflating the two meanings of bug (biological and defect), the story indicates that the term was used in the computer field at that time.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Similarly, the term *debugging* was used in aeronautics before entering the world of computers.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Robert Oppenheimer, director of the WWII atomic bomb Manhattan Project at Los Alamos, used the term in a letter to Dr.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Ernest Lawrence at UC Berkeley, dated October 27, 1944, regarding the recruitment of additional technical staff.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] The Oxford English Dictionary entry for *debug* uses the term *debugging* in reference to airplane engine testing in a 1945 article in the Journal of the Royal Aeronautical Society.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] 50) refers to *debugging* aircraft cameras.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] The seminal article by Gill in 1951 is the earliest in-depth discussion of programming errors, but it does not use the term *bug* or *debugging*.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] In the ACM's digital library, the term *debugging* is first used in three papers from the 1952 ACM National Meetings.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Two of the three use the term in quotation marks.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] By 1963, *debugging* was a common enough term to be mentioned in passing without explanation on page 1 of the CTSS manual.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] As software and electronic systems have become generally more complex, the various common debugging techniques have expanded with more methods to detect anomalies, assess impact, and schedule software patches or full updates to a system.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] The words "anomaly" and "discrepancy" can be used, as being more neutral terms, to avoid the words "error" and "defect" or "bug" where there might be an implication that all so-called *errors*, *defects* or *bugs* must be fixed (at all costs).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Instead, an impact assessment can be made to determine if changes to remove an *anomaly* (or *discrepancy*) would be cost-effective for the system, or perhaps a scheduled new release might render the change(s) unnecessary.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Not all issues are safety-critical or mission-critical in a system.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Also, it is important to avoid the situation where a change might be more upsetting to users, long-term, than living with the known problem(s) (where the "cure would be worse than the disease").
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Basing decisions of the acceptability of some anomalies can avoid a culture of a "zero-defects" mandate, where people might be tempted to deny the existence of problems so that the result would appear as zero *defects*.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Considering the collateral issues, such as the cost-versus-benefit impact assessment, then broader debugging techniques will expand to determine the frequency of anomalies (how often the same "bugs" occur) to help assess their impact to the overall system.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Debugging ranges in complexity from fixing simple errors to performing lengthy and tiresome tasks of data collection, analysis, and scheduling updates.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Debuggers are software tools which enable the programmer to monitor the execution of a program, stop it, restart it, set breakpoints, and change values in memory.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] The term *debugger* can also refer to the person who is doing the debugging.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Generally, high-level programming languages, such as Java, make debugging easier, because they have features such as exception handling and type checking that make real sources of erratic behaviour easier to spot.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] In programming languages such as C or assembly, bugs may cause silent problems such as memory corruption, and it is often difficult to see where the initial problem happened.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] In those cases, memory debugger tools may be needed.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] In certain situations, general purpose software tools that are language specific in nature can be very useful.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] These take the form of *static code analysis tools*.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] These tools look for a very specific set of known problems, some common and some rare, within the source code, concentrating more on the semantics (e.g. data flow) rather than the syntax, as compilers and interpreters do.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Both commercial and free tools exist for various languages; some claim to be able to detect hundreds of different problems.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] These tools can be extremely useful when checking very large source trees, where it is impractical to do code walk-throughs.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] A typical example of a problem detected would be a variable dereference that occurs *before* the variable is assigned a value.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] As another example, some such tools perform strong type checking when the language does not require it.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Thus, they are better at locating likely errors in code that is syntactically correct.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] But these tools have a reputation of false positives, where correct code is flagged as dubious.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] The old Unix *lint* program is an early example.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] For debugging electronic hardware (e.g., computer hardware) as well as low-level software (e.g., BIOSes, device drivers) and firmware, instruments such as oscilloscopes, logic analyzers, or in-circuit emulators (ICEs) are often used, alone or in combination.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] An ICE may perform many of the typical software debugger's tasks on low-level software and firmware.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] The debugging process normally begins with identifying the steps to reproduce the problem.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] This can be a non-trivial task, particularly with parallel processes and some Heisenbugs for example.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] The specific user environment and usage history can also make it difficult to reproduce the problem.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] After the bug is reproduced, the input of the program may need to be simplified to make it easier to debug.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] For example, a bug in a compiler can make it crash when parsing a large source file.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] However, after simplification of the test case, only few lines from the original source file can be sufficient to reproduce the same crash.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Simplification may be done manually using a divide-and-conquer approach, in which the programmer attempts to remove some parts of original test case then checks if the problem still occurs.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] When debugging in a GUI, the programmer can try skipping some user interaction from the original problem description to check if the remaining actions are sufficient for causing the bug to occur.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] After the test case is sufficiently simplified, a programmer can use a debugger tool to examine program states (values of variables, plus the call stack) and track down the origin of the problem(s).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] In simple cases, tracing is just a few print statements which output the values of variables at particular points during the execution of the program.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Automatic bug-fixing is the automatic repair of software bugs without the intervention of a human programmer.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] It is also commonly referred to as *automatic patch generation*, *automatic bug repair*, or *automatic program repair*.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] The typical goal of such techniques is to automatically generate correct patches to eliminate bugs in software programs without causing software regression.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] In contrast to the general purpose computer software design environment, a primary characteristic of embedded environments is the sheer number of different platforms available to the developers (CPU architectures, vendors, operating systems, and their variants).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Embedded systems are, by definition, not general-purpose designs: they are typically developed for a single task (or small range of tasks), and the platform is chosen specifically to optimize that application.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Not only does this fact make life tough for embedded system developers, it also makes debugging and testing of these systems harder as well, since different debugging tools are needed for different platforms.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Despite the challenge of heterogeneity mentioned above, some debuggers have been developed commercially as well as research prototypes.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Examples of commercial solutions come from Green Hills Software, Lauterbach GmbH and Microchip's MPLAB-ICD (for in-circuit debugger).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Two examples of research prototype tools are Aveksha and Flocklab.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] They all leverage a functionality available on low-cost embedded processors, an On-Chip Debug Module (OCDM), whose signals are exposed through a standard JTAG interface.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] They are benchmarked based on how much change to the application is needed and the rate of events that they can keep up with.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Anti-debugging is "the implementation of one or more techniques within computer code that hinders attempts at reverse engineering or debugging a target process".
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] It is actively used by recognized publishers in copy-protection schemas, but is also used by malware to complicate its detection and elimination.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] An early example of anti-debugging existed in early versions of Microsoft Word which, if a debugger was detected, produced a message that said, "The tree of evil bears bitter fruit.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/debugging] Now trashing program disk.", after which it caused the floppy disk drive to emit alarming noises with the intent of scaring the user away from attempting it again.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] An **integrated development environment** (**IDE**) is software that provides a relatively comprehensive set of features for software development.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] An IDE is intended to enhance productivity by providing development features with a consistent user experience as opposed to using separate tools, such as vi, GDB, GCC, and make.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] At a minimum, an IDE typically supports source-code editing, source control, build automation, and debugging.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] An IDE may include support for integrating tools such as a compiler, runtime environment or version control system, but sometimes such tools are bundled with the IDE.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Some IDEs provide special support for constructing a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Many IDEs support object-oriented programming via features such as class browser and object browser.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Typically, an IDE provides special support for one or more programming languages, allowing for features tailored to a language.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Some IDEs can be extended to support additional languages.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Although some IDEs are implemented as an application, some are implemented as a library, often designed for a particular software platform.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] For example, although Eclipse is a platform for which there are many plugins that each provide an IDE experience, the core application does not.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] While modern IDEs are GUI-based, there were IDEs before the availability of windowing systems like Windows and the X Window System.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] For example, Turbo Pascal for MS-DOS has a full-screen, text-based user experience.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] IDEs initially became possible when developing via a console or terminal.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Early systems could not support one, since programs were submitted to a compiler or assembler via punched cards, paper tape, etc.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Dartmouth BASIC was the first language to be created with an IDE (and was also the first to be designed for use while sitting in front of a console or terminal).
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Its IDE (part of the Dartmouth Time-Sharing System) was command-based, and therefore did not look much like the menu-driven, graphical IDEs popular after the advent of the graphical user interface.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] However it integrated editing, file management, compilation, debugging and execution in a manner consistent with a modern IDE.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Maestro I is a product from Softlab Munich and was the world's first integrated development environment for software.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Maestro I was installed for 22,000 programmers worldwide.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Until 1989, 6,000 installations existed in the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Maestro was arguably the world leader in this field during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Today one of the last Maestro I can be found in the Museum of Information Technology at Arlington in Texas.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] One of the first IDEs with a plug-in concept was Softbench.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] In 1995 *Computerwoche* commented that the use of an IDE was not well received by developers since it would fence in their creativity.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] As of August 2023, the most commonly searched for IDEs on Google Search were Visual Studio, Visual Studio Code, and Eclipse.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] , allowing them to be installed on the same IDE at the same time.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Another example is JDoodle, an online cloud-based IDE that supports 88 languages.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] , which are selected between automatically based on file extension, environment or project settings.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] feature usually includes syntax highlighting, it can show both the structures, the language keywords and the syntax errors with visually distinct colors and font effects.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] Code syntax can be continuously validated while it is being edited and errors can be provided an error are introduced instead of the developer waiting until a build is run.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] The IDE may support searching for class and function declarations, usages, variable and field read/write, etc.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] The IDE may also support searching for an implementation of a declaration.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] One typical aim of an IDE is to reduce the configuration necessary to integrate multiple development utilities.
[src:debug-adapter-protocol/integrated-development-environment] An IDE can provide for a cohesive configuration aspect that reduces setup time and therefore increases productivity, especially in cases where learning to use the IDE is faster than otherwise integrating and learning multiple tools.
